    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-05-13T12:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-05-13T12:54:00-05:00" n="292"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <head>292. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Thailand</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d292fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_FGR1"
                            >Ford</persName> Library, National Security Adviser, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> East Asian and Pacific Affairs Staff Files,
                        Box 29, Department of State, Telegrams and Cables. Secret; <gloss
                            target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>; Flash. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>; approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>, Johnson, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_ELS1">Eagleburger</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1975-05-13T17:54:00+00:00">May 13, 1975, 1754Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>111025. Subject: Measures to Obtain Release of the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Mayaguez</hi>. Ref: Bangkok 8690.<note n="2" xml:id="d292fn2">
                        <ref target="#d289">Document 289</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>You are correct in what you have told Prime Minister Khukrit that aircraft
                    launched from Thai bases thus far have been for surveillance purposes only. We
                    understand fully sensitivity of issue, but it is our judgment that if we begin
                    to supply the Thais with advance information they would have no alternative but
                    to pose strong objection.</p>
                <p>Regarding decisions taken but as a matter of overall strategy you should
                    understand that we will be required to utilize U-Tapao as may be necessary in
                    order to secure promptly the release of the vessel and Americans. You are
                    already aware, as indicated in <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 131610Z,<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d292fn3">In <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 131610Z to
                            <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>, the <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                            >JCS</gloss> ordered certain U.S. forces in Thailand to position
                        themselves for action at U-Tapao. (<persName corresp="#p_FGR1"
                            >Ford</persName> Library, National Security Adviser, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> East Asian and Pacific Affairs Staff Files
                        Box 28, Department of Defense, <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>,
                        1)</note> of certain steps being taken. You should not <gloss
                        target="#t_rpt1">rpt</gloss> not give any advance indication to the Thais.
                    We realize that there may be costs with the Thais but the balance of interests
                    requires that we be willing to take whatever risks may be involved in our
                    relations with Thais.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_IRS1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Ingersoll</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
